<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-514-409  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 514 409.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Oct 19 1990 n1536* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Intel aims to breach TeraFLOPS barrier with future massivelyparallel machines.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Intel Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    INTC.andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentParallel ProcessingFloating-Point ArithmeticSupercomputersFuture TechnologiesFuture of ComputingProcessor Speed.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>INTEL AIMS TO BREACH TERAFLOPS BARRIER WITH FUTUREandM;MASSIVELY PARALLEL MACHINESandM;Intel Corp has been staking out its ground in supercomputing into the late1990s and describing its somewhat hybrid vision of machines capable ofproducing one (American) trillion arithmetic operations per second.andP;  Intelsees the TeraFLOPS goal being achieved by using a combination of high speedmicroprocessors and massively parallel processors.andP;  It reckons that by themid-1990s, TFLOPS computing will be a reality and that the impact onscientific advancement will significant.andP;  In areas such as space research andglobal climate modelling, where it is impossible physically to test theories,scientists rely on computation as a substitute to experimentation.andP;  And thefaster they can compute, the quicker they can test their theories.andP;  A globalclimate modelling project that would take a year to compute on current GFLOPScomputers, would take a TFLOPS machine just one day.andP;  This type of modellingis just not attempted at the moment as it takes far too long.andP;  As part of thequest for TFLOPS machines, Intel has embarked on a $27m joint research anddevelopment project with the US Advanced Research Projects Agency.andP;  TheTouchstone project, (CI No 1,338), revealed the first fruits of its labour,the 7.6 GFLOPS Gamma machine, back in December 1989 (CI No 1,517).andP;  Lastmonth the stepup Delta machine began internal testing.andP;  It runs at 33 GFLOPSand comes with up to 1Gb memory.andP;  Intel will formally announce the machinenext month.andP;  The final machine in the series perhaps before the TFLOPS goalis reached, is Sigma, scheduled for the end of 1991.andP;  Sigma should run at 150GFLOPS and support up to 100Gb.andP;  All three machines are based on the 80860chip.andO;</TEXT></DOC>